Further investigations reveal that these effects mainly act via suppressing [TF]-mediated [TG] rather than the NF-kappaB pathway; these effects include a decrease in the phosphorylation level of JNK and a direct inhibition of the activity of p-JNK.

JNK-mediated phosphorylation of c-Jun is currently understood to stimulate the transactivating potency of [TF] (e.g., c-Jun/c-Fos; c-Jun/ATF-2), thereby increasing the expression of [TG] target genes.
